commentText: Yeah, I will be moving to Spain (Madrid) in 1 year with my family as my wife wants to be close to her family (who live in Barcelona but will move to Madrid when we make the move) and I love the country. I'm Australian (Sydney) of Spanish and Peruvian parents. It's the only thing that worries me, the job situation, culturally I will be super happy. Luckily i'm in tech and apparently they value experienced people with good English in the tech industry there so we shall see. Worst thing comes to worse i'll hustle and start my own company and see what happens. Why am I leaving Sydney? Frankly the cost of living here is crazy, it's hard to progress even with a good paying job (which I have always had), plus there is a lack of family and culture here. All you do is work here and grow old and lonely. Sydney is beautiful and hugely multicultural but it's a superficial beauty frankly, used to be so much better but it's changed alot in the last 15 years. And as someone of Spanish and Latino blood it's been hard to not be able to see Latino or Spanish music artists in concert or have good Spanish or Latin american food (since most immigration here nowadays is British or Asian). Spain isn't for everyone but it is for me - the family culture, the food, the ability to easily travel around Europe and to other countries (Australia is so far to everything), the cost of living, the better quality of life when I get to that age, etc. Wish me luck!

commentText: I've lived in Spain 15 years and found 3 jobs over the years on Infojobs.  I work as a software engineer.  After a few years networking getting to know people, I found another job I found buy a referral.   I've only ever had indefinite contracts (indefinido)   What you talk about of people not moving up I think is only true in very small companies or companies with no growth.   Larger companies or growing companies will be more likely to move people up.  You can always switch jobs to move up, but I do agree that the mentality here is not to switch jobs.  People don't want to switch jobs (voluntarily leave)  because they want to have the longevity at the company so if they ever got laid off they would get a larger severance pay.

commentText: Sway Vlogs, let me give you some actual data about jobs&salaries in Spain. In 2020, the percentage of workers with "contrato indefinido" (what you would call 'stable') is slightly over 75% of the total working population. The average annual gross salary is 26,738‚Ç¨ for men, and 21,012‚Ç¨ for women. Of course, the 'most frequent' salary is lower, being 18,469‚Ç¨. For instance, the most frequent salary for an English teacher (High School) is 2,251‚Ç¨ per month. If you take into account that the average difference in cost of living between US and Spain is approx. 30%, the salary of this teacher in Spain would be equivalent to a salary of 2,926‚Ç¨ in the US. Going further, it would be around 40,964‚Ç¨ annually (given that in Spain fourteen payrolls are paid per year). At the current dollar exchange rate (1.21 USD / Euro), we have an equivalent annual salary of about $ 49,566 for this High School teacher. According to payscale.com, the median salary for a high school teacher in the US is $ 50,221 ($ 43,964 with 1-4 years of experience; $ 49,295 with 5-9 years). By the way, if you need to prove that you are professionally qualified to carry out any given activity (excluding those requiring an university degree such as doctors, teachers or lawyers, among others) based on your experience or on unregulated education, you can use what is called a 'certificate of professionalism'. It is issued by the labor authority, the State Public Employment Service or the bodies competent authorities of the Autonomous Communities, and is valid throughout the Spanish territory.
